THANK-YOU, CLARK COUNTY SHERIFFS DEPARTMENT!!
Ashland Elementary School received a generous grant from Sheriff John Ketron and his office to pay for the moving costs of the kindergarten and pre school play set. The play set was originally purchased in 2017 also with funds from the sheriff’s office. Shortly after initial installation, the kindergarten and pre-school building was closed and those classrooms were moved across the street to the elementary building.
Again, thank you to the Clark County Commissioners and the Clark County Sheriffs Department for their help with this project!

ATTENTION PARENTS - FOOD SERVICE NOTICE:

The USDA released a nationwide waiver for all schools to apply for that will extend the Summer Food Service Program (SFSP).

This waiver will allow schools to serve children ages 1-18 in our school/community free of charge for both breakfast and lunch until December 31, 2020.

Thanks to the efforts of our Food Service Director, Juanita Encinias, USD 220 has submitted the necessary documents and is awaiting approval. Once we receive the final approval status, all meals served will become free until the end of the waiver date or unless USDA funds are exhausted.

Giving Back!!
Ashland Elementary Students Jacee Walker and Jocelyn Hazen operated a lemonade stand today in the parking lot of Ashland’s Food Pantry. They sold lemonade and bags of home made cookies for $1.00 each. They then donated half of the money raised back to the food pantry.
Now that’s making a difference!
The rest of the story...
After the girls sold out of lemonade and cookies, they were able to donate $100. To the food pantry.
Receiving the donation were Leanne Pike, Linda Redger, and Becky Luerman snd Sherre Sherre Goodnight Harrington
Good job girls!!

Dear USD 220 patrons.

As we all prepare for the busy fall sports seasons that will be starting next week, please understand that each school may have different requirements for fans who attend events. We will do our best to communicate those to the various parent groups via email, but patrons will need to review the information before attending the events.
Likely, fans will be asked to wear masks before entering gyms. Some schools may limit the number of fans allowed to attend. Some schools may check temperatures before allowing you to enter their facilities.
Therefore we ask that you be cooperative and give grace to our neighbors. Remember that our number one job is to keep everyone safe and our schools open.
Thanks

post_text:
Dear ASHLAND Patrons:
As we get closer to hosting indoor events such as volleyball, we wanted to let everyone know about the guidelines that we will be following.
For all indoor events, we strongly encourage all attendees to wear masks and practice social distancing-when possible. We certainly don’t want to discourage anyone from attending an event, but until the mask mandate is lifted, we humbly ask for your compliance.
Outdoor events such as tennis and football would not fall under any mandate. Additionally, we will not be asking for volunteers to collect gate money. Rather, there will be donation boxes available should patrons wish to contribute. Money collected at sporting events goes to help defray the cost of holding our numerous activities.
Thanks for your support and understanding.

post_text:
Hello Bluejays! We are so excited to see you and can't wait for school to start on Monday! Grades 5-12 please plan to join us at AHS on Friday, August 14th from 1:00pm-4:00pm for a come-and-go Open House:

* Come and go anytime between 1pm and 4pm.
* Pick up your class schedule
* See the building eagerly awaiting your return
* Walk through your school day finding your classes
*Say "hi" to your teachers as they are available.
* Find your locker
------As a reminder, this will be the only time available to "set up" your locker. There will not be time allotted on the first day. Please remember that stickers and materials that can cause damage are not permitted.
-------- 5th & 6th grade students are assigned lockers by their classroom teachers for the purpose of material storage only (like a cubbie) and may not decorate/customize, etc. their locker.

Please remember that everyone entering the building will have temperature checked and masks must be worn. We have some in the office if you forget yours.

We will see you Friday!

post_text:
We are so proud of the AR points our students have earned reading these past few months. The AR class totals for the 2019-2020 school year which wrapped up this week are:

6th= 457
7th=120.4
8th=199.4
9th=53.6
10th=339.5
11th=151.3
12th= 238.7

Look at those crazy amazing numbers!

These points do not represent how awesome each person is for reading, but simply represent the applicable AR test points. The winning class is the 2019-2020 5th grade classwith a whopping 1,083.9 AR points! Five people were super readers and earned an extra super reward! Way to go! Students not in the 5th who earned 100 or more points also earned a prize. Even if you did not take AR Tests, your brain will thank you as studies show frequent reading keeps away degenerative neurological diseases and decreases anxiety.

Due to recommendations for social gathering the AR Party is being cancelled. In its place, individual pizza coupons for Sam's Pizza Barn will be given to each student in last year's winning class.

post_text:
Dear Parents and Community Members:

USD 220 will be holding our 8th grade promotion and High School commencement on Sunday, July 5th.

The promotion ceremony begins at 4:00 PM, while the Baccalaureate will begin at 5:00 PM, and Graduation at 5:30 PM.

During this event, social distancing guidelines will be in effect, reducing our seating capacity. Therefore, each student's family will have a section reserved on the gym floor with overflow family seating on the south side . Community members and friends will have limited seating on the north side.

Additionally, we encourage everyone to wear a mask if you choose to attend, especially those who are at risk, may have been exposed to large groups or gatherings, or been to an area with a high infection rate.

This event will be live streamed for those who would rather watch the event instead of attending in person.

We appreciate your support and understanding as we must comply with specific social distancing guidelines for the safety of our students, staff, and patrons.

Thank you.

post_text:
USD 220 Area Residents:

With the changes all of us are making the past few weeks, and the cancellation of school activities, the USD 220 Yearbook is also making adjustments. One is that we are adding a two-page spread, documenting the many ways the pandemic has affected students and staff. We'd like to include the community - parents and others - and how everyone's made adjustments. If you would like, email any photos (original size if from phones) to jjanes@usd220.net by May 10, and be sure to add a relevant description for each image for its caption.

Please email photos/descriptions by May 10 to jjanes@usd220.net and we'll add all we can to the special yearbook spread.

Thank you - stay safe and healthy!

- AHS Yearbook Staff

post_text:
With week 1 of online learning, virtual classes, and learning packets quickly coming to an end, I want to express my thanks and appreciation to our staff, students, and parents for working together to make this transition a success. I have been able to virtually visit several classes, and "wow" what a great learning experience we are all having. Thank you to our teachers for working diligently in planning and preparing last week, and thank you to all our students.

As questions continue to arise, we have created some direction for you below:
1. Internet Issues (Connectivity) - call the school; reboot your Chromebook and router; contact service provider.
2. Chromebook Issues - call the school; reboot your Chromebook; if issues continue, call the school and schedule a time to drop off Chromebook and pick up a loaner.
3. Food Service - call the school for all questions.
4. Learning Packets - email the teacher.
5. Health & Well-Being - contact Haley Walker

post_text:
USD 220 Students,

𝕎𝕖 𝕞𝕚𝕤𝕤 𝕪𝕠𝕦! 💛💙

We are about to embark on a journey together through uncharted waters. You have incredible teachers that have been working incredibly hard for you! They are planning to deliver an outstanding education!

There are a few things I want you to know before Monday.

*You are not in this alone!
*We are here for you!
*Take some time to clean out your email inbox, now.
*Check your email often!
*Keep a healthy schedule (eating and sleeping)
*Organization - you’ll need to stay organized- don’t let it overwhelm you, you got this!

If you need additional help, let us know. Finish this year strong!

While it’s important to process the loss of the traditional end of the school year, we also have the opportunity to celebrate this experience, and work together to find solutions. Remember, you are not alone!

💙💛WE WILL FINISH STRONG💛💙

Get outside and try to find them all. Unscramble the letters to find out what the phrase is.
Be safe and have fun.
—AES Teachers

post_text:
To Our Students:

We, the teachers and staff of USD 220, want to make sure you know how much we care about your well-being and education. This new challenge will only serve to provide us the opportunity to make sure we stay engaged with you on a different playing field. Over the next couple weeks, the staff will work to develop a plan to make sure all students are able to continue their classes. Although this may look different, we are still here to help.

For our Seniors...we understand that this will mean many missed events and activities. Today, those may seem to be the most important part of your life, but as difficult for you as it is, we are all here to help. When we are able, we will make sure to provide you the proper recognition you all deserve for your hard work.

Together we can make sure we meet the needs of everyone. Together we will move forward. We are all Bluejays4Life!

More information will be provided as it comes in.

Respectfully,
Mr. Jamie Wetig, Ed.S.
Superintendent of Schools

This will be available for pick up by parents living in Ashland, with limited delivery options in Englewood and the outlying areas. Students will be charged meal prices based on their current status. Meals will be provided for all days the school would have been in operation (based on our 4-day school week).

The Archery Course is right “on target!” Seth Harrington and his crew of volunteers have been extremely busy building Ashland’s newest activity. The Archery Club has 16 student members in grades 5th through 12th.
There have been many folks who have volunteered their time and effort to bring the range along this far. There is still a lot of work to do, but the change is dramatic.
They have their first meet of the season tomorrow ( Saturday ) The public is invited to come out and watch.

post_text:
These are the 3rd and 4th grade winners from the soil conservation office’s annual poster contest.

Each year the members of these classes complete a large unit in soil and water conservation. The project includes all types of labs and experiments in the classroom as well as field trips that show them conservation techniques around Clark County.
Adam Elliott and Heather Grigsby are a big part of this project. In addition to conducting the field trips and providing resources, their office helps to sponsor the poster contest. The winners were announced today, and they treated the kids to fresh donuts. Kelly Hazen was also on hand to help with the ceremony. Thank you to all who help with this yearly project.

post_text:
KINDNESS IN ACTION!
Last night at the home basketball games against Minneola the freshmen class and their sponsor, Haley Walker, hosted a bake sale and a 50/50 drawing. Normally, those types of events are held to raise money for proms or senior trips. This event was much different. The money did not go into the Class of 2023’s account. Instead, all of the money raised was donated to three families from Minneola whose moms are battling breast cancer.
The Dennison’s, the Dewell’s, and the Cordero’s from Minneola all have high school students who play basketball. Mrs. Walker and her class decided that they wanted to raise some funds when the Clark County rivals got together on the court. Thanks to the generosity of patrons from both towns, a total of $661.00 dollars was raised last night. After the 50/50 raffle was paid, each family received $150.00.
Thank you to Haley Walker and her Class of 2023 for showing us what good neighbors do for each other.

Instead, all of the money raised was donated to three families from Minneola whose moms are battling breast cancer.

post_text:
Kansas State University: USDA Tele-Presence Grant:

In April of 2019, USD 220 was contacted by the Rural Education Center at Kansas State University, and became a part of a rural education consortium. One of the benefits of this relationship is having the opportunity to be involved with grants for rural education.
I am excited to inform you that the Rural Education Center has received what is being called a Tele-Presence grant from the USDA. This is a new “distance learning grant” in which Ashland will be a “hub-site” for K-State. This grant will provide equipment and technology to USD 220 in order to provide students with STEM (Science, Technology, Engineering, Math) opportunities in partnership with our classroom teachers.
This is another opportunity for USD 220 to on the forefront of innovation, instruction, and redesigning the educational process. More to come...
text:
Kansas State University: USDA Tele-Presence Grant:

In April of 2019, USD 220 was contacted by the Rural Education Center at Kansas State University, and became a part of a rural education consortium. One of the benefits of this relationship is having the opportunity to be involved with grants for rural education.
I am excited to inform you that the Rural Education Center has received what is being called a Tele-Presence grant from the USDA. This is a new “distance learning grant” in which Ashland will be a “hub-site” for K-State. This grant will provide equipment and technology to USD 220 in order to provide students with STEM (Science, Technology, Engineering, Math) opportunities in partnership with our classroom teachers.
This is another opportunity for USD 220 to on the forefront of innovation, instruction, and redesigning the educational process. More to come...
